h Jose, Candido, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Ricardo, Carolina, Enrique, Fidel, Juan Carlos, Luis.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name from <i>camps</i> ‘fields’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","English: habitational name from Castle Camps or Shudy Camps (Cambridgeshire), or from Camps in Nazeing (Essex)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camp","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Van de Camp</b>) and North German: from <i>camp</i> ‘enclosed, fenced, or hedged piece of land, field’, from Latin <i>campus</i> ‘plain’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived by such a field. Compare   Kamp  .","English: from Middle English <i>kempe</i> ‘warrior’; see   Kemp  . The spelling <i>Camp</i> may be due to the influence of Old English <i>camp</i> ‘battle’ and <i>campian</i> ‘to fight’, or of Old French <i>campion</i> ‘warrior, champion’.","French: mainly southern form of   Champ  ."]}]},{"name":"Adelaide","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin (via French  <b>Adélaïde</b> ), from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘kind, sort’. It was borne in the 10th century by the wife of the Holy Roman Emperor Otto the Great. She became regent after his death and was revered as a saint. The given name increased in popularity in England during the 19th century, when it was borne by the wife of King William IV; she was the daughter of the ruler of the German duchy of Saxe-Meiningen. The Australian city of Adelaide was named in her honour."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adelaide DE COMPS was born about 1075, in Dauphiné, France, her father, Arnaud De Comps, was -18 and her mother, Alix De Montclus, was -19. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Arnaud II Lambert De La Flotte. She died in 1188, at the age of 114."},"et":{"Abt 1115–1188":"umbes 1075–1188","1075–1188":"1075–1188","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1125–1188":"1125–1188","1075–1186":"1075–1186","1